<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-060-321 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 337 339</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Sept 11 1991 n167 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications (UK)1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft to write code for next IBM operating system? (OS/2)(PCUser News) (Brief Article)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zuin, Daniela.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product development)Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Topic:     ProgrammingProduct DevelopmentStrategic PlanningAnalysisContractsProgramming (Computers)OS/2Operating systemsCooperative Agreement.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Despite Microsoft's public split with IBM, the software giant is stillcommitted to writing code based on its New Technology (NT) for IBM.andM;Bill Gates, president and chief executive officer of Microsoft, told PC Userthat IBM has already invested heavily in the code.andP;  &quot;IBM has always made ahuge commitment to the NT base technology,&quot; Gates said.andP;  (For the fullinterview, see page 50)andM;As late as last April, Microsoft was unsure whether to introduce NT as an OS/2 or a Windows product.andP;  It is now likely that the product shipped to IBMwill be the the same code that was originally referred to as OS/2 3.0.andM;IBM refuses to say what the code will be used for.andP;  &quot;There is no commitmentfrom us to produce a product with this code,&quot; said Gordon Bell, IBM UK's OS/2marketing and support manager.andM;Microsoft announced in August that it would not market a product called OS/23.0.andP;  But the company has not abandoned its work integrating OS/2 with NT.andO;&quot;We will have an optional subsystem with OS/2 APIs available on Windows NT,so that OS/2 customers can migrate to the latest Windows product,&quot; saidAndrew King, Microsoft UK's Windows product manager.andM;IBM is left in an awkward position regarding development.andP;  The latest dealsstruck with Apple and Borland point to a new long-term PC strategy, and nofinal products are expected for another five years.andP;  In the meantime, IBM hasto decide how its OS/2 strategy will develop.andM;Mark Lillycrop, business analyst for Xephon, said: &quot;IBM has never had muchOS/2 development expertise of its own; instead it has relied heavily onMicrosoft.andP;  IBM has to weigh up both technical and marketing aspects todecide whether or not it needs NT technology,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;But IBM will bemore inclined to work on a proprietary system.&quot;andM;OS/2 users at Sun Alliance welcomed Microsoft's implied involvement in thefuture of OS/2.andP;  Rick Williams, senior technical analyst at Sun, said: &quot;Sincethe split andlsqb;between IBM and Microsoftandrsqb; we have had a bitter taste in ourmouths.andP;  To hear they are working together again is a pleasant surprise.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>